Yep—monthlyOnDay won’t cover “run every day at HH:mm.”
Let’s add a dailyAtTime schedule type.

1) Config (events.json)

Example:

{
  "id": "unpaidContractInquiry_daily_extract",
  "name": "Daily unpaid extract",
  "when": ["insert","update"],
  "conditions": { "logic": "OR", "rules": [ { "op": "becameNotNull", "field": "policyId" } ] },
  "schedule": {
    "type": "dailyAtTime",
    "time": "09:00",
    "tz": "Asia/Tokyo",
    "businessDays": true   // optional; if true skip Sat/Sun
  }
}

2) Scheduler change (Java)

Add a case to your existing SchedulePlanner.compute(...):

case "dailyattime": {
    LocalTime t = parseTimeOrDefault(evt.schedule.time, LocalTime.of(9, 0));
    ZonedDateTime now = ZonedDateTime.now(zone);
    ZonedDateTime candidate = now.withHour(t.getHour()).withMinute(t.getMinute())
                                 .withSecond(0).withNano(0);

    if (!candidate.isAfter(now)) {
        candidate = candidate.plusDays(1);
    }

    if (Boolean.TRUE.equals(evt.schedule.businessDays)) {
        while (candidate.getDayOfWeek() == DayOfWeek.SATURDAY ||
               candidate.getDayOfWeek() == DayOfWeek.SUNDAY) {
            candidate = candidate.plusDays(1);
        }
    }
    return candidate.toOffsetDateTime();
}

(Keep your existing immediate, atField, afterDaysFromField, monthlyOnDay cases as-is.)

That’s it—now you can model Realtime (immediate), Daily (dailyAtTime), and Batch/Monthly (monthlyOnDay) explicitly.